               <msContents>
                  <summary> This manuscript of the <title>Tārīkh-i ‘Ālamgīr-i S̲ānī</title> (History
                     of Ālamgīr II), provides a highly detailed account of the brief, six-year reign
                     of the Mughal ruler <persName>Emperor ‘Ālamgīr II (b. 1699, r.
                        1754–1759)</persName>.</summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_873-item1">
                     <author key="person_f407" change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="en" type="anonymous">Anonymous</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6930">Tārīkh-i ‘Alamgīr-i
                        S̲ānī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_6930">تاریخ عالمگیر ثانی</title>
                     <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_873-item1-item1">
                        <title>Book One</title>
                        <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ
                              (folio 1b):</locus> حمد و بیحد احدی را رسد که میزان ادراک هیچ فردی
                           حقیقت ذانش نمی‌سنجد و ستایش دنیا یش بی قیاس ثمدی را سزد که رد مقیاس قیاس
                           فهم دقیقه شناس اشخاص ماهیت صفاتش نم گنجد... </incipit>
                        <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="229a" to="229a"> برگ ۳۵۲ر (folio
                              229a):</locus> بشد ختم این داستان وسیع * بتوقیع مرمان عالم مطیع </explicit>
                        <note>Moreley notes <q>Here should follow the names of Shah Alam's children
                              (sons + daughters).</q></note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_873-item1-item2">
                        <title>Book Two</title>
                        <note>Moreley notes <q>Nine distichs precede this commencement in my other
                              ms of this work.</q></note>
                        <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmalla"><locus from="233b" to="233b"> برگ
                              ۲۳۳پ (folio 233b):</locus> الحمد لله الذي جعل السلاطين الاعظم
                           والخواقين المكرم حامي الملة والدين المتين ونور المنور شموس معدلتهم افاق
                           العالم والعالمين... </incipit>
                        <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="352a" to="352a"> برگ ۳۵۲ر (folio
                              352a):</locus> مکن در سخن پیش از ین اهتمام *‌ سخن بر همین ختم شد و
                           السّلام</explicit>
                        <colophon>تمت تمام شد.</colophon>
                        <colophon>Uninformative colophon.</colophon>

                     </msItem>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of thin-weight, straight-grained, externally sized and
                           polished, ivory-coloured <material>paper</material> probably handmade in
                           the <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~20 laid
                           lines per 20 mm and few discernible chain lines and average thickness of
                           63 microns on the first ten folios.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="373">373 folios, 3 flyleaves (ff. ii +
                              373 + i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>247</height>
                              <width>158</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>208</height>
                              <width>106</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>



                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Pencilled Arabic numerals added to the upper-left
                           corners of the a sides when catalogued.</foliation>

                        <collation> Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the
                              lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>


                        <condition>In fair condition, with moderate water and insect damage and
                           historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>


                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="17" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 17
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="inkBlack inkRed"> Written in clear black
                        nasta‘līq with red subheaders and markings. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="ib" to="ib">first right flyleaf b
                        side (f. ib)</locus> bears several English notes in various hands, number
                        <q>Nº 4</q>, and a price of 10 Rupees.<lb/> The <locus from="iia" to="iia"
                        >second right flyleaf b side (f. iia)</locus> bears a price of <q>£2 2-</q>
                     at top, with a note in Persian describes the volume as anonymous,full of
                     errors, and doubtful quotes, which if corrected, would prove a valuable
                     contribution.<lb/> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> numbered <q>Nº
                        3</q> at top.<lb/> Folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> bears a note in
                        <persName role="fmo seal ins" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/56966054/"
                        key="person_56966054">William Hook Morley</persName>'s hand: <q>This MS
                        comprises<lb/>both volumes of the work. WM</q>.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplate and label:</label> The <locus from="iib" to="iib">final right
                        flyleaf b side (f. iib)</locus> bears earlier Lindesiana label <q
                        xml:lang="en">Persian MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">79</hi></q>, with the
                     number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">873</q> written aside.<lb/>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left doublure</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> without a shelfmark. </additions>

                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1825">
                        <p>Probably bound in the <origPlace cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</origPlace>.</p>
                        <p>Comparatively heavy and rough endpapers added to the beginning and end.
                           Sewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, and chevron endbands of
                           yellow and red silk threads twined at <locus from="Head" to="Head"
                              >head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered
                           in full claret-coloured goatskin <material>leather</material> over
                              <material>pasteboards</material>, tight-backed, cut flush with the
                           textblock edges, with defined joints, but without a flap (Type III
                           binding per Deroche). Interior doublures of the same leather, with their
                           excess widths adhered as hinges conneting the texblock to the cover, with
                           wide strips of paper applied over top to disguise the joins.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Board margins blind-tooled with insular dots, with
                           double fillets either side. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus>
                           titled <q>AHWÁL-I<lb/> 'ALAMGÍR<lb/> SÁNÍ</q></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>254</height>
                              <width>166</width>
                              <depth>52</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition, with
                           broken tail cap, and internal break by the first folio.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Three relief-carved, black oval seal impressions bearing the emblem
                        and name of former owner <persName role="fmo seal ins"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/56966054/" key="person_56966054">William Hook
                           Morley</persName> on the <locus>second right flyleaf a side (f. iia)
                        </locus> and folios <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, <locus from="352b"
                           to="352b">352b</locus>.</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="armorial">
                        <p><heraldry>A fleur de lis crowns and protrudes from the mouth of a cat,
                              encircled by a buckled belt bearing inscribed <q xml:lang="en">WILLIAM
                                 • H • MORLEY • MIDDLE • TEMPLE</q></heraldry>.</p>
                        <decoNote type="seal" subtype="dimensions"><p>
                              <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>40</height>
                                 <width>28</width>
                              </dimensions>
                           </p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but probably <origDate cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1775" notAfter="1825">late 18th to early
                        19th centuries CE</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/70111987008653"
                           key="place_7008653">Britain</placeName> remain unclear, barrister and
                           <orgName>Royal Asiatic Society</orgName> librarian <persName
                           role="fmo seal ins" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/56966054/"
                           key="person_56966054">William Hook Morley (1815–1860)</persName>,
                        acquired the volume from an unidentified source.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Morley's death, his executors sold his library through the
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/157917019" key="person_157917019">S. Leigh
                           Sotheby &amp; John Wilkinson</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1861-03-16">16 March 1861</date> (p. 67, lot 1037), but it
                        apparently did not sell. Thereafter, London bookseller <persName
                           type="standard" role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/"
                           key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold the
                        volume, one of nine oriental manuscripts, on behalf of Morley's executors to
                           <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1867-01-17"
                           >17 Jan. 1867</date> for £1, 5 shillings, for the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                           >1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           type="corporation" role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John
                           Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
